15:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-12","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Rate Mechanics"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Both exchanges use 8-hour funding intervals with rates calculated from perpetual-index basis and open interest imbalance. Gate.io applies a wider funding rate cap of ±2% compared to OKX's ±0.75%, leading to more extreme rates on low-liquidity pairs. OKX implements portfolio margin which can reduce effective funding costs through cross-collateralization. Gate.io's extensive altcoin coverage creates more arbitrage opportunities but with higher execution risk."}]]}]
16:["$","$L17",null,{"items":[{"question":"Which exchange has better funding rate transparency between OKX and Gate.io?","answer":"OKX provides more detailed funding rate analytics and historical data through their API. Gate.io shows basic funding information but lacks comprehensive rate forecasting tools that professional arbitrageurs require."},{"question":"How do margin requirements compare for funding rate arbitrage?","answer":"OKX's portfolio margin mode allows up to 20x leverage with cross-collateralization, reducing capital requirements. Gate.io uses isolated margin by default with standard 10-20x leverage depending on the perpetual contract tier."},{"question":"Which platform handles funding rate spikes better during volatile periods?","answer":"Gate.io's ±2% funding rate caps allow for more extreme rates that can be profitable but risky. OKX's tighter ±0.75% caps provide more predictable funding costs but limit arbitrage upside during market stress."},{"question":"What are the key API differences for automated funding strategies?","answer":"OKX offers WebSocket streaming for real-time funding rate updates and better order execution APIs. Gate.io has comprehensive REST endpoints but less reliable WebSocket connections, making it more suitable for lower-frequency strategies."}]}]
